MUNICIPAL SCHOOLS IN AHMEDABAD The Municipal School Board, established in 1827 with its first school, Sheth Lalbhai Dalpatbhai Munshi School No. 1 near Panchkuva. Subsequently, the first Gujarati Vernacular school was established with the assistance of British officer Alexander Kinloch Forbes and poet Dalpatram. The city's first girls' school was founded in 1851. By the 1946-47 academic year, municipal schools had 41,662 students. Presently, the AMC School Board oversees 449 schools, with 337 Upper Primary and 112 Primary schools, employing 4255 teachers and 203 principals, serving 165,946 students. The pupil- teacher ratio stands at 39:1. With a century-long legacy, the Municipal School Board has seen alumni make noteworthy contributions to the nation and society. • Total 449 Schools • Teachers – 4,255 no. • Principals – 203 no. • Students – 1,65,946 Nos. • Pupil-Teacher Ratio – 39 : 1 • Zone – 12, Clusters – 87 no. With the implementation of the National Education Policy (NEP) 2020, the AMC School Board has recognized the imperative of upgrading educational infrastructure and enhancing learning outcomes through Activity-Based Learning. As a pioneering step, the school board team has decided to establish one smart school in each of the 48 wards of Ahmedabad city, envisioning them as lighthouse projects. These schools will serve as models for innovative teaching methodologies and modern facilities. Upon evaluating the effectiveness and success of these pilot projects, the aim is to replicate their approach and strategies across other parts of the city, ensuring equitable access to quality education for all students.
PROJECT BACKGROUND Municipal schools in Ahmedabad were considered non aspirational for majority of parents and are riddled with issues like inadequate physical & digital infrastructure, traditional pedagogy, substandard delivery methods which contributes to high dropout and low enrolment rates in municipal schools. The school building and other physical infrastructures were 50-60 years old. And the IT infrastructure have been implemented in piecemeal, need holistic approach focused on enhancement of learning environment in classroom. Lecture Based Teaching – Teachers used text book and notes to deliver lecture. A rote-based teaching method dominated. In this method, students write exams and may score reasonably well, but they will lack skills such as problem solving, critical thinking or thinking on one’s feet. The number one issue is teacher’s inhibition towards use of data and technology in learning management. It is important for administrators to build capacity of teacher shall be developed to use digital platform and data points. National Education Policy, Pragna (Pravrutti Dwara Gnan) – Activity based learning (ABL), GoG, Atal Tinkering Lab, GoI STEM lab – Samagra Shiksha, GoG, Gyankunj, GoG & NEP 2.2 Smart School Stakeholder Opinion: The project has garnered positive feedback from teachers and the community, with the infrastructure designed to last 8-10 years with proper maintenance and capacity building. Replicability: The results of the pilot project are encouraging, and we are planning to extend this solution. In India there are more than one million govt. schools where this model can be replicated. Key Success Factor: Political will and leadership, Identification & training of teachers as a champion change maker. A self-improving system based on specific need of each school Municipal schools were non aspirational Physical & digital infrastructure Traditional pedagogy Teacher’s inhibition towards technology Alignment with NEP and state govt. policy

Ahmedabad School Board SIGNAL SCHOOL PROJECT
The Municipal School Board Ahmedabad, in collaboration with the Gujarat State Legal Authority, has decided to provide free education to children found begging at traffic intersections. The initiative includes 12 mobile buses equipped with fully furnished classrooms, provision of nutritious meals, medical checkups, competitions, stage performances, uniforms, mid-day meals, education kits, and school bags. The Municipal School Board in Gujarat embarked on this ambitious mission in March 2022, initially serving 139 children with 10 buses. Bridge courses were provided to prepare them for mainstream education, and all children were integrated by June 2022. In the second phase, inaugurated by dignitaries, enrollment increased to 123 students in the second semester. The third phase, inaugurated by the Chief Justice of the High Court of Gujarat in June 2023, now serves 151 students, marking the highest number of beneficiaries to date. PROJECT BRIEF SIGNAL SCHOOL BHIKSHA NAHI SHIKSHA A total 13 mobile buses as school on wheels 150+ children are now studying in smart schools A bond of ₹5000 for each students School Preparation Activites Situations that led to the present innovation Process of conceiving the idea Strategy and method In Ahmedabad a disheartening sight unfolded daily: children, once full of potential, now relegated to begging at bustling traffic intersections. Their aimless wanderings at these crossroads revealed a stark truth they were not receiving an education, thus denied their fundamental "Right to Education." The 'Right to Education' Act provides children aged 6 to 14 with fundamental education rights. Through a Special Training Program featuring the 'PRAGNA COURSE', these children were prepared for formal schooling. A comprehensive survey identified children begging at key signals citywide, ensuring none were missed. These children were promptly enrolled in mobile schools, granting them immediate educational access.
Key Components • Identified children aged 6-14 at various crossroads. • Designed child-friendly buses for AMTS. • Mobile Bus equipped with teaching aids, books, blackboard, LED display, CCTV, Wi-Fi, First Aid, GPS, sports kit, toys, and sound system. • Routes and timetables for SIGNAL SCHOOL buses. • Recruited and trained two teachers for each bus. • Curriculum, textbooks, and stationery for 'Special Training Program’. • Free Mid-Day Meals. • Regular medical check-ups for children. • Completed 'School Readiness Program' from March to April 2022. • Bridge course for school enrollment • A bond of ₹5000 in the name of each student. Upon passing Class VIII, beneficiaries will receive the principal amount along with interest. • Mahatma Gandhi International School will allocate 20 percent of its sanctioned capacity of Class I to children from 'Signal Schools.' • MoU with Anant National University to provide a skill development program Challenges Faced & Lessons Learned: Parents initially viewed children as economic assets, making education difficult. They struggled with discipline, unfamiliarity with structured learning, and classroom routines due to their free- spirited nature. After Innovation: Children gained access to nearby schools, enrolled after completing the readiness program. Increased awareness led more parents to enroll their children in these signal schools. PROJECT BRIEF National Award for Innovations and Good Practices in Educational Administration by the National Institute of Educational Planning and Administration.
